  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mupaka Shamba Letu : The border, our livelihood - Peacebuilding through strengthened cross border trade in the Great Lakes region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Direct beneficiaries:
1,200 small scale women cross border traders (FPCTs &#x2013; femmes petites commercantes transfrontalieres) in total, including additional support to 800 FPCTs currently supported by the MSL project and support to 400 new FPCTs selected at new 4 border sites
720 spouses of FPCTs (including 480 spouses of existing MSL FPCT beneficiaries and 240 new FPCT spouses)
60 FPCT Associations and Cooperatives (5 for each of the 12 project sites) including 36 currently supported by MSL and 24 new ACTs, comprising around 6,000 small cross-border traders
600 border officials
120 women managers of SMEs in all 8 border areas
600 local, municipal, provincial and national authorities in the 3 countries
Total direct beneficiaries = 8,640</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Overall, the program contributes to more inclusive community relations across borders in the Great Lakes region and strengthened cooperation between authorities and communities for a more lasting peace.
With the support of the Embassy of Sweden in Kigali, Rwanda (hereon referred to as &#x201C;Sida Rwanda&#x201D;), Alert will scale up high-impact initiatives under the MSL project to 4 new project sites/ 2 borders, building on achievements and lessons learned and adding new strategic activities in other sites. The funding will allow the MSL project to run for one additional year (2023) to focus on consolidating change, ensuring results are sustained after the project and recovering from delays experienced as a result of the Covid-19 crisis.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To strengthen the capacities of women small-scale cross-border traders in border areas of DRC, Rwanda, and Burundi to jointly challenge gender dynamics that contribute to conflict in their communities and the wider region, and use their influence to promote greater social cohesion and regional cooperation</narrative>
  </description>
